text=:Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild%0a:Essential: {Category.LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild$:essential}%0a:Title: L Rhotacism in Japanese English%0a:Author: Russell_E%0a:Section: E%0a:Completed: 28.04.2021 - 21:12%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a----%0a%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210511-223355-820710#%0a* [-11.05.2021 - 15:33-] || TA_mason marked as complete%0a#foxend 210511-223355-820710#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0aSummary: \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aAn instance of avoiding discrimination in the world of chess streaming.%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aLink: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yAUtOTA6--A%0a%0aThis clip is actually an instance of avoiding discrimination, and it’s rather lighthearted. The phenomenon is rhotacism of /l/ in Japanese English. %0a%0aThe situation in the clip is a bit more complicated than it seems if you don’t know who the people are. International Master Levy “GothamChess” Rozman is a native speaker of General American English, and speaks a few other languages. Grandmaster Hikaru Nakamura is half-Japanese, and he grew up with his white American mother and Sri Lankan-American stepfather in the USA. He is a native speaker of General American English. He is not a native speaker of Japanese, but he learned to speak some after childhood. So, Hikaru himself has never used /l/-rhotacism naturally. In this situation, the relationship between language and race is quite complicated.%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:GradedBy: TA_mason:)
